               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340904-199-person1227">
                  EDWARD 
                  SMITH
               <interp inst="t18340904-199-person1227" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-199-person1227" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-199-person1227" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am shopman to Mr. Stephen Fawcett. He <rs id="t18340904-199-viclabel1128" type="occupation">keeps a carpet shop</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340904-199-victim1226 t18340904-199-viclabel1128"></join>, on <placeName id="t18340904-199-crimeloc1129">Islington-green</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18340904-199-crimeloc1129" type="placeName" value="Islington-green"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18340904-199-crimeloc1129" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340904-199-off1126 t18340904-199-crimeloc1129"></join> - on the 4th of July, the officer came in about six o'clock, and asked if we missed any thing - I looked, and missed four pieces of moreen from the side of the door - I went to the stationhouse, and identified them.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340904-199-person1228">
                  THOMAS 
                  HOBBS KING
               <interp inst="t18340904-199-person1228" type="surname" value="HOBBS KING"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-199-person1228" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-199-person1228" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             (police-constable N 248). On the 4th of July I was sitting at my window on Islington-green - I saw the two prisoners and another cross the green, to Mr. Fawcett's shop - I knew them, and watched them - Stewart stood against the prosecutor's door, and Baxter walked backwards and forwards twice - he then took two pieces of moreen and gave them to Stewart - the other man then took two pieces and gave them to Stewart - I ran down and took Stewart with the four pieces on his shoulder - I asked him what he was going to do with them - he said, what was that to me - I said it was to me, he must go to the station-house - I seized Baxter - Stewart then threw down these pieces, and tried to get away - I got assistance, and he was secured.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. CHURCHILL. Q. How far was Stewart from the shop door when the property was taken? A. The distance of the window; two or three yards.</p>
               <p>EDWARD SMITH. This is my master's property - it has our mark on it.</p>
               <p>Baxter's Defence. I was merely passing when this man was taken - I never saw him before.</p>
               <p>Stewart's Defence. I was passing the green, and a man asked me to carry these.</p>
               <p>BAXTER - <rs id="t18340904-199-verdict1130" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18340904-199-verdict1130" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 22.</p>
               <p>STEWART - <rs id="t18340904-199-verdict1131" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18340904-199-verdict1131" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 18.</p>
